    description: `Rozon Kay Masail is a detailed Urdu-language book that provides a systematic treatment of the issues and rulings (masail) related to fasting (sawm) in Islam. Categorized under the Hadith section, this book grounds its fiqh-based discussions in authenticated Hadith narrations, ensuring that every ruling presented is directly traceable to the Quran and the verified Sunnah of the Prophet Muhammad (SAW). The book serves as a comprehensive reference for Muslims who want to understand the practical and legal dimensions of fasting throughout the year — not only during the obligatory fast of Ramadan but also voluntary fasting, expiatory fasting, and the specific fasts recommended on particular days in the Islamic calendar.

The book begins with the foundational rulings: who is obligated to fast, the conditions that make fasting obligatory, the correct time for beginning and ending the fast, the requirement of intention (niyyah), and the definition of what constitutes a valid fast according to Islamic law. It then addresses the things that invalidate the fast — intentional eating, drinking, and sexual relations — and distinguishes between actions that definitively break the fast and those about which there is scholarly discussion. A particularly valuable section covers common scenarios that cause confusion among Muslims, such as the use of eye drops, ear drops, toothpaste, asthma inhalers, blood tests, injections, and nasal sprays during fasting hours, with clear fiqh-based answers for each.

The book provides detailed coverage of the rulings for those who are exempt from fasting or have special circumstances: the traveler (musafir), the elderly, the chronically ill, pregnant and nursing women, and those experiencing temporary sickness. The concepts of qada (making up missed fasts), fidya (feeding a poor person), and kaffarah (expiation for intentionally breaking a fast) are each explained with their specific conditions and requirements. Additional chapters address the merits and virtues of fasting on specific days — Mondays and Thursdays, the three white days of each lunar month, the day of Arafah, the day of Ashura, and the six days of Shawwal — all supported by Hadith evidence. The book also covers I'tikaf (spiritual retreat), the fiqh of Suhoor and Iftar, the Zakat al-Fitr obligation, and the recommended supplications for fasting. Written in clear and methodical Urdu, Rozon Kay Masail is an indispensable handbook for every Muslim household and a reliable resource for scholars, Imams, and students of Islamic knowledge.`,
